fields.description:
If you use Wiki markup to reference a repository in the Objective for a review, when the e-mail notification is sent for the review the markup isn't rendered into a link.

For example, the following Objective:

{noformat}Testing wiki markup: {cs:id=5|rep=SubversionHTTP}{noformat}

The content of the e-mail will be as follows:

{noformat}
...

Statement of Objectives:
Testing wiki markup: {cs:id=5|rep=SubversionHTTP}

State: Review

...
{noformat}

We just upgraded to 2.x and none of the Project tab Commits sub-links, or Users tab Commit tab sub links work in Crucible. Steps to reproduce:
   0. Update Jetty to 6.1.20
   1. Click on Projects
   2. Choose a project
   3. The all activity sub link should be active
   4. click on Commits link
   5. Get the error "The requested resource cannot be found"

There is nothing in the logs! Where do 404s get logged?

Here is an example URL that is broken:

https://example.com/fisheye/project/REPO?max=30&projectKey=REPO&view=fe&@asv=fe

We noticed that you can remove the projectKey param to get it to work:
https://example.com/fisheye/project/REPO?max=30&view=fe&@asv=fe

This only occurs if you update to jetty 6.1.20, which we are bound to do in the future. 

From Customer:

{quote}
I believe the removal of this else block results in the merging of the parameter from the path and the query string.  This was apparently to fix a bug but in the case of FE it causes parameters to be merged and not handled correctly.

I believe that the JETTY change was correct and this should be considered an FE bug.  I suggest that either the REST handling remove duplicate parameters or that the downstream action not toString() the String[] array when evaluating the resource.  The latter is preferable.

http://fisheye.codehaus.org/changelog/jetty?cs=5328

{code}
if  (parameters.containsKey(name))
                         {
 	                      rewrite_old_query = true;
 	                           }
	                         else
	                           {
 	                               Object values=entry.getValue();
	                               for (int i=0;i<LazyList.size(values);i++)
	                               {
	                                   parameters.add(name, LazyList.get(values, i));
	                               }
                           }


{code}
{quote}

On: [https://extranet.atlassian.com/crucible/browse/FE/trunk/src/java/com/cenqua/crucible/actions/ReviewBaseAction.java?r=65346#to164]

{quote}
This string compare is a total fail and I guess we should be able to compare JiraIssue.getStatus().getId() with the id that the admin filled out in the JIRA server subtask admin section.
{quote}

As raised in review: [https://extranet.atlassian.com/crucible/cru/CR-FE-3816#c33524]

I added JIRA to my OAuth configuration in Fisheye/Crucible but after adding the gadget to my JIRA dashboard, I see this in the Crucible logs every time I load my dashboard:

{code}
09:44:38 ERROR - Error handling trusted applications authentication attempt:OLD_CERT;   Certificate too old. Application: {0} Certificate Created: {1} Timeout: {2};    ["jira:10756294","Sat Aug 07 09:44:35 CDT 2010","1000"]
{code}

I'm not sure how the cert can be too old when both JIRA and Crucible are new installs and I just setup the trusted apps + OAuth.

This appeared after I clicked "Login & Authenticate" in the gadget window.

{noformat}
com.cenqua.fisheye.rep.DbException
Group 'atlassian-staff' does not exist
{noformat}

We should provide suggestions on 404 pages when a path cannot be found. For example, hitting:

{{https://extranet.atlassian.com/crucible/changelog/FE/src/content/static/2static/aui}}

Could show:
{noformat}
Did you mean:
 * /FE/trunk/src/content/static/2static/aui
 * /FE/recently-updated-branch/src/content/static/2static/aui
{noformat}

This can be done easily and efficiently with Geoff's suffix path matcher which he implemented for Patch anchoring.
